Disease-Disease Associations and Visualization

Mustafa S Ascha

July 5, 2017

0.1 Motivation and Goals

  • Copious amounts of transactions data are produced not just in industry, but in healthcare claims
  • The curse of dimensionality makes explaining some of the relationships between item co-occurrence difficult
  • Solution: use visualization as a decision support tool–by displaying large amounts of data in concise ways, new patterns may be revealed

0.2 What we have

  • Medicare data representing inpatient claims at the national level.
  • About 350,000 records of inpatient visits paid by Medicare
  • 5 to 10 diagnoses per inpatient record
  • Demographic data such as age, race, income quartile of patient zip code
  • You can learn more about Medicare data here

0.3 What we want

Zhou X, Menche J, Barabasi AL, Sharma A. Human symptoms-disease network. Nature communications; 26 June 2014. DOI: 10.1038/ncomms5212. http://barabasi.com/f/479.pdf

  • Reduces dimensionality

0.5 Disease-disease relationships

  • Size of node represents frequency of the diagnosis among all diagnoses
  • Thickness of the edge connecting two nodes represents ‘lift’, which is how much more often we see the pair than we would expect if they occurred independently
  • Selected relationships based on co-incidence metrics
  • The following is a small (fewer nodes/edges) version of the associations, you can find the medium version here and the large version here

0.6 Obstetrics and related diagnoses

Looking at the above disease-disease relationship network, obstetrics-related trauma represents a prominent proportion of Medicare inpatient claims. One such condition is diabetes (we might expect it to be gestational diabetes), which is itself associated with presence of a previous C-section.

Even without medical knowledge, we might expect that the population of patients with a previous c-section would have a greater age than its counterpart because it usually takes about nine months to have a baby. Here is a plot showing evidence for this hypothesis:
